I know, I know, it’s been too long! But fret not, your constant checking and refreshing of my blog has not gone unnoticed because I present to you a brand new website to look at!

<a title="Jerikho Prototype" href="http://harryfox.me/portfolio/jerikho" target="_blank"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-80" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/spaceship2-300x265.png" alt="spaceship2" width="300" height="265" /></a>

<a title="Jerikho Prototype" href="http://harryfox.me/portfolio/jerikho" target="_blank">Click here or on the 1980s spaceman to see it. It\'s got parallax, it\'s responsive, there\'s a front-end AND a back-end! I just know you\'ll love it!</a>

But wait, there’s more! I also created an entire brand identity for this one too. And not just for fun, this was for a real person with a real business, so you KNOW it’s legit!
<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-79" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/spaceship1-290x300.png" alt="spaceship1" width="290" height="300" />
<em>your face</em></p>
Let me walk you through it. Here is the brief I was given:

<strong>"I want it to look pretty swish."</strong>

So, there’s a lot of freedom to be taken advantage of there which is fine by me, so I made the decision to start developing a framework for the website concurrently to developing a brand identity.

Below is a little window into the whole branding process I went through...

Here’s a trimmed down version of my discovery document which elaborates and expands the branding guide I was given whilst remaining consistent to the original idea. I used this to inform all later design decisions:

<hr />

<ul style="text-align: center;">Jerikho</ul>
<p style="text-align: center;">“Communication - unity”</p>
<strong>Summary</strong>

Modern use of social networking allows for better connection to those we know, but can also isolate us from the individuals and communities on our door-step. Increasingly, it seems that our neighbours are strangers and, as a result, so much valuable and rewarding human interaction is lost in favour of digital interaction.

Jerikho seeks to combine digital and human interaction by connecting those members of a community who are willing to work with their neighbours for free. Jerikho facilitates altruistic human interaction at the micro level and in doing so bring communities closer together.

<strong>The Name</strong>

Jerikho (the app) is spelled differently from Jericho (the place) for several reasons.

To Reference its Place of Origin:

<em>Jericho, Oxford, is an historic suburb located just outside the old city wall and birthplace of the Jerikho app. Oxford’s Jericho was originally a place for travellers to rest if they had reached the city after the gates had closed.</em>

To Reference Themes of Altruism

<em>Luke 10:25 and the Parable of the Good Samaritan. The Good Samaritan was travelling from Jerusalem to Jericho when he decided to help a man attacked by robbers and Jesus uses this story to demonstrate the inherent value in helping one’s neighbours.</em>

To Retain its own Identity

<em>Spelt with a ‘K’, Jerikho is not relieved of its religious connotations because they are unavoidable given the similarity the words bare and their identical pronunciation. However, a different spelling makes it a different word with its own meaning. It is a homophone, inspired in form by the themes of the Parable, but with its own unique identity.</em>

<strong>Who Will Use Jerikho?</strong>

Job Seekers

<em>Whether unemployed or looking for a change in career, Jerikho can be used as a way of demonstrating your interest in certain kinds of work. The app logs jobs completed along with a reference to the person for whom it was completed and this may be used as evidence when looking for work.</em>

Duke of Edinburgh Students and those on similar development programmes

The Person Next Door

<em>Jerikho is for anyone and everyone. If you have something to offer your community, something valuable and helpful, then connect with those that live around you. Get to know the people around you. Everyone in a community shares a vested interest in where they live and realising those interests can only be achieved by working together.</em>

<strong>What Kind of Person Uses Jerikho?</strong>

Individuals who are:
<ul>
	<li><em>socially conscious</em></li>
	<li><em>altruistic with their time and energy</em></li>
	<li><em>interested in improving the social wellbeing of the place they live</em></li>
	<li><em>friendly</em></li>
	<li><em><em>trusting</em></em>

<hr />

</li>
</ul>
So hopefully you’ve got a better picture in your head of what I’m working with. Now here’s what I did:

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wordmap.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-81" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/wordmap.jpg" alt="wordmap" width="653" height="384" /></a>

I threw together as many synonyms and extrapolations of the words and themes from the discovery document as I could think of and made connections that I felt were logical or made obvious progressions.

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logodesign1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logodesign1.jpg" alt="logodesign1" width="653" height="490" /></a>

From there I started sketching symbols and images that I felt emulated the key words identified in the word map. Of particular importance were the word ‘community’. Connecting imagery, interlocking or intertwining imagery eventually came to the forefront of my thinking and I felt the best representation of a community united was the linked arms folks.

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logodesign2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-76" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logodesign2.jpg" alt="logodesign2" width="547" height="799" /></a>

Without wishing to emulate other similar logos that feature little stick people in them and with the hands conjuring strong feelings of charity I decided to go down the typographical route and eventually plumped for a large J connected with a smaller, reversed J. The suggestion here is that the two letters might otherwise fall over without the support of one another and are stronger for joining together. (Some bullshit like that anyway).

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/colourhierarchy.png"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-66" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/colourhierarchy-204x300.png" alt="colourhierarchy" width="204" height="300" /></a>

In the same panel above you can also see the colours I picked, named, and hierarchically ordered, but here they are again. This process came more naturally as I made the logo on PhotoShop: I started with a variant on Oxford Blue and then chose a brighter, friendlier blue, a more serious grey, and an accent pink for diversity.

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/screenshot.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-78" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/screenshot-300x187.jpg" alt="screenshot" width="300" height="187" /></a>

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/photoshopping.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-77" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/photoshopping-300x224.jpg" alt="photoshopping" width="300" height="224" /></a>

Here are some other versions that I discarded!

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-4.png"><img class="aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-73" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-4-150x150.png" alt="logo-4" width="150" height="150" /></a>

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-3.png"><img class="aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-72" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-3-150x150.png" alt="logo-3" width="150" height="150" /></a>

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-2.png"><img class="aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-71" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-2-150x150.png" alt="logo-2" width="150" height="150" /></a>

<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-1.png"><img class="aligncenter size-thumbnail wp-image-70" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/logo-1-150x150.png" alt="logo-1" width="150" height="150" /></a>

<hr />

Finally I picked three fonts to use on the website which were recognisable, fitted the theme, and were easy to read. Again, if you want to see the finished product, <a title="Jerikho Prototype" href="http://harryfox.me/portfolio/jerikho" target="_blank">click here.</a>

Well goodness me you made it all the way to the end huh? Thank you very much for reading this. Even if you’re not looking for someone to make you a branded website it’s still nice to think that someone actually looks at this stuff, I know my parents bloody don’t. Yeah that’s right, I’m talking to you, Dad. Mr “I don’t follow you on Facebook, but we’re still friends”! Pff.

Anyway, um, yeah thanks for getting to the bottom. I really really enjoyed going through the branding process on this project and creating something at the end which had meaning and value. Everything you see at the end has a reason for being there, not like Year 10 Design Tech where I made a shark logo ‘coz sharks are BEAST.

As partial payment for spending time here on my website (and possibly telling your friends about it?? huh? Maybe someone who wants to pay me to do this for them??) here is a great life-hack for you.
<p style="text-align: center;">Leftover crusts from the pizza you just ate?
<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/lifehack1.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-67" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/lifehack1-300x224.jpg" alt="lifehack1" width="300" height="224" /></a>
Save them!</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Use them as breadsticks to dip in your soup!</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/lifehack2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-68" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/lifehack2-300x224.jpg" alt="lifehack2" width="300" height="224" /></a></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Totally disappointing
<a href="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/lifehack3.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-69" src="http://harryfox.me/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/lifehack3.jpg" alt="lifehack3" width="192" height="144" /></a></p>
In other news, I haven’t worn underpants since Wednesday.

K bye, I love you!

